How to Finance the Green Transition
New York – This week, world leaders have gathered in New York at the United Nations to assess the global battle against climate change and submit new pledges for emission reductions.
The climate crisis is grave, and our actions are not fast enough.
We are not shifting into high gear quickly enough.
Faster progress requires efforts from both public and private sectors.
Luckily, thanks to the work of the Climate Finance Leadership Initiative (CFLI), there is growing private sector collaboration to combat climate change.
Under the leadership of United Nations Climate Action Special Envoy Michael Bloomberg, CFLI was established with the aim of mobilizing global private capital to address this critical issue.
This month, CFLI released a new report titled "Financing the Low Carbon Future," which outlines how to expand green finance to support a smooth low-carbon economic transition and identifies public-private partnership opportunities to achieve the Paris Climate Agreement targets set in 2015.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) is the largest multilateral investor in climate-related projects worldwide.
But now, in response to calls from European Heads of State and the newly elected President of the European Commission Ursula von der Leyen, we are prepared to step up our ambition and strengthen the EIB's role as a specialized climate bank within the EU.
EIB will mainstream climate considerations, focusing on low-carbon investments, and will invest at least 1 trillion euros in low-carbon projects over the next ten years.
To achieve this goal, at least 50% of EIB financing will be directed towards climate action and environmental sustainability by 2025.
By the end of 2020, we will align all our financing activities with the objectives of the Paris Climate Agreement.
As an important first step, we will exclude energy projects that rely on fossil fuels.
In addition, we will position EIB as a green finance incubator, committed to mobilizing other resources to help economies transition to a low-carbon future.
As an EU bank, our task is to invest in Europe's future, and the most critical issue among them is climate change.
The more urgent the climate crisis, the stronger our determination.
This summer, Europe suffered from record-high temperatures and crop failures due to last year's drought.
Many developing countries have had similar experiences.
Floods and other climate-induced phenomena cost major cities billions of dollars annually, and more lives are at risk.
But the climate crisis is also an opportunity because funding for new green infrastructure can create jobs, stimulate economic growth, and reduce air pollution that plagues many of the world's cities.
Shifting investment models could accelerate the transition away from fossil fuels. This transition has already begun.
The market is increasingly favoring clean energy over fossil fuels.
In 2011, while half of the US coal-fired power plants were retired, the clean energy industry created 3.3 million jobs, compared to fewer than 100,000 in the coal sector.
In addition, more and more American cities and states have committed to achieving net-zero emissions by 2050.
They will receive support from Beyond Carbon, a program launched last year by the Bloomberg Philanthropies aimed at supporting full decarbonization of the US economy.
As an international community, we must not only invest in clean energy but also reduce investment in dirty energy.
Currently, in terms of fossil fuel subsidies, we are effectively spending money to promote climate change and air pollution.
This public money should be directed towards technologies that can drive the green transition, such as electric vehicles.
These investments will generate huge returns, including reducing the enormous cost to public health caused by air pollution.
Moreover, we can take many steps to guide necessary funding.
First, we must improve data and disclosure standards.
For a long time, companies and investors have had no idea about climate-related risks, not knowing the rationale for reducing carbon emissions or protecting assets from extreme weather impacts.
This is starting to change.
The recommendations from the Task Force on Climate-related Financial Disclosures are guiding companies to allocate capital in more sustainable ways, and enabling investors to reward those that are taking climate action seriously.
Next, we must clarify investment risks associated with green finance.
Cities account for more than 70% of carbon dioxide emissions, but only a few developing world cities have access to credit ratings.
The result is that the overall investment in clean public transport, energy-efficient buildings, and other projects to reduce emissions has been affected.
Governments and listed banks must step up efforts to help cities attract capital for these projects, including through initiatives such as the Global Covenant of Mayors for Climate & Energy, which is supported by the EIB and co-led by the Bloomberg Philanthropies.
Third, we need to modernize our power grids.
Refunds and tax incentives for wind and solar power have promoted their expansion and reduced costs for businesses and consumers.
Now, we should introduce similar programs to accelerate the deployment of battery storage and other emerging technologies, and speed up the resolution of intermittency issues.
In addition, better grid connectivity would allow regions with excess wind and solar power to supply regions facing shortages.
The government can play a leadership role in both areas, encouraging more private investment in clean power.
Finally, we must continue to expand the green investment market.
In 2007, the EIB issued the world's first green bond on the Luxembourg Stock Exchange, and since then, the green bond market has expanded to $136 billion.
But compared to a global bond market worth $100 trillion, this is just a drop in the bucket.
Therefore, the EIB is helping to develop sustainable finance standard classifications for the EU so that investors can compare like-for-like projects, as they do with conventional bonds.
Better and more information about the carbon footprint of investments would enable investors to make informed decisions and thus encourage more private investment into low-carbon projects.
This is how we finance the green transition.
